-- Australian, New Zealand Stocks: BHP, Centro, Citigold, Rio Tinto, Woodside
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-26T06:38:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-26/australian-new-zealand-stocks-bhp-centro-citigold-rio-tinto-woodside.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index 
climbed 0.6 percent to 4,486.10 at the 4:10 p.m. close of
trading in Sydney. New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  advanced 0.9
percent to 3,021.19 at the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures for September delivery rose
for a fifth straight day on July 23, gaining 0.6 percent to
$3.185 a pound in New York.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
advanced 0.4 percent to A$39.82.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the
world’s third-largest mining company, increased 0.6 percent to
A$70.25.  
 Centro Properties Group  (CNP AU) surged 3.5 percent to 15
Australian cents. The Australian property trust is seeking a
partner to manage 50 shopping centers and buy part of the
company’s equity in the syndicates holding them, the Australian
newspaper reported, citing a document sent to prospective buyers.  
 Citigold Corp. Ltd.  (CTO AU), a gold explorer, jumped 8.1
percent to 9.3 Australian cents. Zhaojin Mining Industry Co.
said a unit is buying a 2 percent stake in Citigold for A$2
million. Zhaojin will continue talks for a “substantial
position” in Citigold, the Chinese company said in a statement
to the Hong Kong exchange.  
 Commonwealth Property Office Fund  (CPA AU) lost 0.5 percent
to 97.5 Australian cents. The property trust was downgraded to
“underweight” from “neutral” at JPMorgan Chase & Co. by
equity analyst  Michael Scott .  
      Harvey Norman Holdings Ltd.  (HVN AU), Australia’s biggest
electrical and furniture retailer, lost 3 percent to A$3.54. The
company posted a 4 percent drop in domestic fourth-quarter sales
after the government withdrew its stimulus spending.  
  Linc Energy Ltd.  (LNC AU) jumped 6.5 percent to A$1.635
after the company said it received written offers for coal
assets it is seeking to sell.  
      QBE Insurance Group Ltd.  (QBE AU), Australia’s biggest
insurer by market value, slumped 5.6 percent to A$16.97 after
its first-half insurance profit margin missed the company’s
target range.  
      Wesfarmers Ltd.  (WES AU), Australia’s second-largest
retailer, advanced 3.2 percent to A$30.08. The company said
sales at its Coles unit rose in the fourth quarter as the
division’s convenience stores and revamped fresh food areas in
supermarkets drew more customers.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, advanced 0.5 percent to A$42.13.
Woodside had its rating raised to “hold” from “sell” by
analysts at Citigroup Inc. led by  Mark Greenwood .  
